    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/5641710580/lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="Can you remember what Imperatives are? That&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s when we use a verb as an instruction or a command to basically tell someone to do something. And can you remember how we form these in Hindi? We actually have three different ways of doing it, one for each of the ways of saying &lsquo;You&rsquo; -&nbsp;&#2310;&#2346; aap, &#2340;&#2369;&#2350; tum and &#2340;&#2370; too. So for example, using the verb &#2326;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366; khaanaa - To eat, we&rsquo;d say&hellip;





 &nbsp;&nbsp;&#2326;&#2366;&#2311;&#2319; khaaie - Please eat, or &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&#2326;&#2366;&#2323;&nbsp;khaao - Eat, or &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&#2326;&#2366;&nbsp;khaa - Eat!


 This should just be revision, but if you&rsquo;re confused about this, or the about differences between the three words above, then be sure to read back over&nbsp;Lesson #75: Imperatives Part 1, Lesson #77: Imperatives Part 2 and Lesson #80 Imperatives Part 3.&nbsp;


 Today we&rsquo;re going to learn how to turn these Imperatives into the negative case. This is just adding the word 'don&rsquo;t&rsquo;! So we&rsquo;ll learn how to say something like 'Don&rsquo;t do that&rsquo;, 'Don&rsquo;t go&rsquo;, 'Don&rsquo;t bring food&rsquo; etc. So are you ready to get straight into it? &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366; acchaa - great!&nbsp;


 All you need to know is that we use the word &#2344; na&nbsp;to mean 'Don&rsquo;t&rsquo; for the &#2310;&#2346; aap case and the word &#2350;&#2340; mat&nbsp;to mean 'Don&rsquo;t&rsquo; for the &#2340;&#2369;&#2350; tum and &#2340;&#2370; too cases. Both these words usually go just behind the verb. And that&rsquo;s all you need to know really! How easy is that hey? Let me show you some examples&hellip;





&#2358;&#2348;&#2381;&#2342;&#2325;&#2379;&#2358; &#2325;&#2379; &#2344; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2367;&#2319;  shabdkosh ko na parhie  - Please don&rsquo;t read the dictionary


 Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done here? We&rsquo;ve used the verb &#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2344;&#2366; parhnaa in the &#2310;&#2346; aap imperative to give us&nbsp;&#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2367;&#2319; parhie - Please read. Adding the &#2344; na just behind changes it to 'Please don&rsquo;t read&rsquo;.&nbsp;


 Here we also use the Postpostition &#2325;&#2379; ko to&nbsp;show that we are talking about a specific dictionary rather than just dictionaries in general! Did you follow that? Ready for another example?&nbsp;





&#2346;&#2381;&#2352;&#2375;&#2350; &#2325;&#2379; &#2309;&#2326;&#2364;&#2348;&#2366;&#2352; &#2350;&#2340; &#2342;&#2379; prem ko akhbaar mat do - Don&rsquo;t give the newspaper to Prem


 This time we&rsquo;ve just used &#2350;&#2340; &#2342;&#2379; mat do to mean 'Don&rsquo;t give&rsquo;. (Remember that in the &#2340;&#2369;&#2350; tum case &#2342;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366; denaa is irregular and becomes &#2342;&#2379;&nbsp;do) Can you see how easy this is?&nbsp;





&#2350;&#2375;&#2332;&#2364; &#2346;&#2352; &#2350;&#2340; &#2348;&#2376;&#2336; mez par mat baith - Don&rsquo;t sit on the table!


 Here we&rsquo;re using the verb &#2348;&#2376;&#2336;&#2344;&#2366; baithnaa in the most informal &#2340;&#2370; too case. Imagine a Mother shouting a her child to get off from the table! Ready for some more examples?





&#2342;&#2352;&#2357;&#2366;&#2332;&#2364;&#2375; &#2325;&#2379; &#2344; &#2348;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342; &#2325;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319; darvaaze ko na band keejie  - Please don&rsquo;t close the door


 The word &#2348;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342; band means 'closed&rsquo;, and so &#2348;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342; &#2325;&#2352;&#2344;&#2366; band karnaa means 'to close&rsquo;. (Remember here that the verb &#2325;&#2352;&#2344;&#2366; karnaa is Irregular in the &#2310;&#2346; aap imperative - we say &#2325;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319; keejie).





&#2350;&#2375;&#2352;&#2366; &#2346;&#2366;&#2344;&#2368; &#2350;&#2340; &#2346;&#2367;&#2351;&#2379; meraa paanee mat piyo - Don&rsquo;t drink my water


 Remember that&nbsp;&#2346;&#2368;&#2344;&#2366; peenaa - To drink becomes &#2346;&#2367;&#2351;&#2379;&nbsp;piyo in the &#2340;&#2369;&#2350;&nbsp;tum imperative!&nbsp;


&#2350;&#2340; &#2342;&#2380;&#2337;&#2364;mat daur - Don&rsquo;t run!


&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#2350;&#2340; &#2348;&#2379;&#2354; mat bol - Don&rsquo;t speak! &nbsp;


 Can you follow each of the examples above? Make sure you can spot which form of the Imperative we are using each time! Be sure to ask me in a comment below if you have any questions. Are you ready for a few more final examples for today?&nbsp;





&#2350;&#2375;&#2352;&#2375; &#2328;&#2352; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2360;&#2367;&#2327;&#2352;&#2375;&#2335; &#2344; &#2346;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319; mere ghar men sigaret na peejie - Please don&rsquo;t smoke in my house


 In Hindi we literally say &#2360;&#2367;&#2327;&#2352;&#2375;&#2335; &#2346;&#2368;&#2344;&#2366;  sigaret peenaa - 'To drink a cigarette&rsquo; to mean 'To smoke a cigarette&rsquo;. Weird hey!





&#2309;&#2349;&#2368; &#2342;&#2369;&#2325;&#2366;&#2344; &#2350;&#2340; &#2332;&#2366;&#2323;&nbsp; abhee dukaan mat jaao - Don&rsquo;t go to the shop now


 Wow ok! That&rsquo;s it for now. How&rsquo;s that been? Can you follow each of the sentences? Have you got any questions? Leave a comment just below and let me know. Try and make so of your own sentences like this!


