                     --><!-- <li><a class="label" href="/ask" id="ask">Ask me anything!</a></li> --><li><a class="label" href="../../intro"><small> - Introduction</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../vowels"><small>- Vowels</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../consonants"><small>- Consonants</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../convo"><small>- Conversational</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../beginner"><small> - Beginner's</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../intermediate"><small> - Intermediate</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../numbers"><small> - Numbers</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../urdu"><small> - Urdu</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../all"><small> - All Lessons</small></a></li><!--  <li class="galleries"><div class="label">Lessons</div><div class="menu-wrap"><ul class="menu"><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/intro">Introduction</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/vowels">Vowels</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/consonants">Consonants</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/convo">Conversational</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/beginner">Beginner's Grammar</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/intermediate">Intermediate</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/numbers">Numbers</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/urdu">Urdu</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/all">All Lessons</a></li></ul></div></li><li id="search"><div class="label">Search<div class="icon"></div></div><div class="form-wrap"><div class="icon"></div><form action="/search" id="search-form" method="get"><input id="search-field" name="q" onblur="if (this.value == '') {this.value = 'Search tags';}" onfocus="if (this.value == 'Search tags') {this.value = '';}" type="text" value="Search tags" /></form></div></li> --><li><a class="label" href="../../legal">Legal</a> </li><li><a class="label" href="../../links">Links</a> </li> 

          </ul></div><div id="posts"><article class="post type-text" id="5641710580"><aside class="metadata not-custom-page"><a class="timestamp" href="lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives-dont">May 19th, 2011</a><!--  
                               <a class="note-count" href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/5641710580/lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives#notes">54 notes</a> --><a class="comment-count" href="lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives-dont#disqus_thread"></a><script type="text/javascript">
    var disqus_shortname = 'learninghindi';

    (function () {
        var s = document.createElement('script'); s.async = true;
        s.type = 'text/javascript';
        s.src = '//' + disqus_shortname + '.disqus.com/count.js';
        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives-dont">Lesson #111: Imperatives Part 4: Negatives - &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t&hellip;&rdquo;</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Can you remember what Imperatives are? That&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s when we use a verb as an instruction or a command to basically tell someone to do something. And can you remember how we form these in Hindi? We actually have three different ways of doing it, one for each of the ways of saying &lsquo;You&rsquo; -&nbsp;<big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap</em>, <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> and <big><big>&#2340;&#2370;</big></big> <em>too</em>. So for example, using the verb <big><big>&#2326;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>khaanaa</em> - To eat, we&rsquo;d say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lld0viBz7P1qzfx8l.png"></p><p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&#2326;&#2366;&#2311;&#2319;</big></big> <em>khaaie</em> - Please eat, or &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&#2366;&#2323;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>khaao</em> - Eat, or &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>khaa</em> - Eat!</p><p>This should just be revision, but if you&rsquo;re confused about this, or the about differences between the three words above, then be sure to read back over&nbsp;<a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1695175480/lesson-75-imperatives-part-1-aap">Lesson #75: Imperatives Part 1</a>, <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/2111368263/lesson-77-imperatives-part-2-tum">Lesson #77: Imperatives Part 2</a> and <a href="../2337937750/lesson-80-imperatives-part-3-too">Lesson #80 Imperatives Part 3</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>Today we&rsquo;re going to learn how to turn these Imperatives into the negative case. This is just adding the word 'don&rsquo;t&rsquo;! So we&rsquo;ll learn how to say something like 'Don&rsquo;t do that&rsquo;, 'Don&rsquo;t go&rsquo;, 'Don&rsquo;t bring food&rsquo; etc. So are you ready to get straight into it? <big><big>&#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366;</big></big> <em>acchaa</em> - great!&nbsp;</p><p>All you need to know is that we use the word <big><big>&#2344;</big></big> <em>na</em>&nbsp;to mean 'Don&rsquo;t&rsquo; for the <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap</em> case and the word <big><big>&#2350;&#2340;</big></big> <em>mat</em>&nbsp;to mean 'Don&rsquo;t&rsquo; for the <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> and <big><big>&#2340;&#2370;</big></big> <em>too</em> cases. Both these words usually go just behind the verb. And that&rsquo;s all you need to know really! How easy is that hey? Let me show you some examples&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_llenlhapbJ1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2358;&#2348;&#2381;&#2342;&#2325;&#2379;&#2358; &#2325;&#2379; &#2344; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2367;&#2319;<br></big></big> <em>shabdkosh ko na parhie</em> <br> - Please don&rsquo;t read the dictionary</p><p>Can you see what we&rsquo;ve done here? We&rsquo;ve used the verb <big><big>&#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>parhnaa</em> in the <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap</em> imperative to give us&nbsp;<big><big>&#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <em>parhie</em> - Please read. Adding the <big><big>&#2344;</big></big> <em>na</em> just behind changes it to 'Please don&rsquo;t read&rsquo;.&nbsp;</p><p>Here we also use the Postpostition <big><big>&#2325;&#2379;</big></big> <em>ko </em>to&nbsp;show that we are talking about a specific dictionary rather than just dictionaries in general! Did you follow that? Ready for another example?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lld1hhyC301qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2346;&#2381;&#2352;&#2375;&#2350; &#2325;&#2379; &#2309;&#2326;&#2364;&#2348;&#2366;&#2352; &#2350;&#2340; &#2342;&#2379;</big></big> <em>prem ko akhbaar mat do</em> <br>- Don&rsquo;t give the newspaper to Prem</p><p>This time we&rsquo;ve just used <big><big>&#2350;&#2340; &#2342;&#2379;</big></big> <em>mat do</em> to mean 'Don&rsquo;t give&rsquo;. (Remember that in the <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> case <big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>denaa</em> is irregular and becomes <big><big>&#2342;&#2379;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>do</em>) Can you see how easy this is?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_llemw55wda1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2375;&#2332;&#2364; &#2346;&#2352; &#2350;&#2340; &#2348;&#2376;&#2336;</big></big> <em>mez par mat baith</em><br>- Don&rsquo;t sit on the table!</p><p>Here we&rsquo;re using the verb <big><big>&#2348;&#2376;&#2336;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>baithnaa</em> in the most informal <big><big>&#2340;&#2370;</big></big> <em>too</em> case. Imagine a Mother shouting a her child to get off from the table! Ready for some more examples?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lld24jN2eI1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2342;&#2352;&#2357;&#2366;&#2332;&#2364;&#2375; &#2325;&#2379; &#2344; &#2348;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342; &#2325;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <br><em>darvaaze ko na band keejie </em><br>- Please don&rsquo;t close the door</p><p>The word <big><big>&#2348;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342;</big></big> <em>band</em> means 'closed&rsquo;, and so <big><big>&#2348;&#2344;&#2381;&#2342; &#2325;&#2352;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>band karnaa</em> means 'to close&rsquo;. (Remember here that the verb <big><big>&#2325;&#2352;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>karnaa</em> is Irregular in the <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap</em> imperative - we say <big><big>&#2325;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319; </big></big><em>keejie</em>).</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/f34ad39e1c206b47f90664462a7dd646/tumblr_inline_mnfkruZTE91qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2375;&#2352;&#2366; &#2346;&#2366;&#2344;&#2368; &#2350;&#2340; &#2346;&#2367;&#2351;&#2379;</big></big> <br><em>meraa paanee mat piyo</em><br>- Don&rsquo;t drink my water</p><p>Remember that&nbsp;<big><big>&#2346;&#2368;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>peenaa</em> - To drink becomes <big><big>&#2346;&#2367;&#2351;&#2379;&nbsp;</big></big><em>piyo</em> in the <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;&nbsp;</big></big><em>tum</em> imperative!&nbsp;</p><p class="center">&#2350;&#2340; &#2342;&#2380;&#2337;&#2364;<em>mat daur </em>- Don&rsquo;t run!<img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_llewcpU6C91qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_llgc72uHBe1qzfx8l.jpg">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<big><big>&#2350;&#2340; &#2348;&#2379;&#2354;</big></big> <em>mat bol</em> - Don&rsquo;t speak! &nbsp;</p><p>Can you follow each of the examples above? Make sure you can spot which form of the Imperative we are using each time! Be sure to ask me in a comment below if you have any questions. Are you ready for a few more final examples for today?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_llgcn7BtYi1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2375;&#2352;&#2375; &#2328;&#2352; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2360;&#2367;&#2327;&#2352;&#2375;&#2335; &#2344; &#2346;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319; <br></big></big><em>mere ghar men sigaret na peejie</em> <br>- Please don&rsquo;t smoke in my house</p><p>In Hindi we literally say <big><big>&#2360;&#2367;&#2327;&#2352;&#2375;&#2335; &#2346;&#2368;&#2344;&#2366; </big></big> <em>sigaret peenaa</em> - 'To drink a cigarette&rsquo; to mean 'To smoke a cigarette&rsquo;. Weird hey!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_llgdnpcEve1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2309;&#2349;&#2368; &#2342;&#2369;&#2325;&#2366;&#2344; &#2350;&#2340; &#2332;&#2366;&#2323;</big></big>&nbsp;<br><em>abhee dukaan mat jaao</em><br>- Don&rsquo;t go to the shop now</p><p>Wow ok! That&rsquo;s it for now. How&rsquo;s that been? Can you follow each of the sentences? Have you got any questions? Leave a comment just below and let me know. Try and make so of your own sentences like this!</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1695175480/lesson-75-imperatives-part-1-aap">Imperatives Part 1</a> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/2111368263/lesson-77-imperatives-part-2-tum">Imperatives Part 2 </a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="../2337937750/lesson-80-imperatives-part-3-too">Imperatives Part 3</a>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <a href="lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives-dont">Imperatives Part 4</a></p><p><a href="../../beginner">Click to go back to Beginners Grammar</a>.&nbsp;</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/grammar">grammar</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/imperatives">imperatives</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/may2011">may2011</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/verbs">verbs</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="5641710580" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_5641710580"><iframe id="like_iframe_5641710580" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=5641710580&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=sCgNHvzr" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_5641710580"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.t